\fs28 \cf4 \cb3 WordPress Developer Resources\
Dec 28, 2023\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 WordPress 5.8 comes with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://make.wordpress.org/core/2021/06/25/introducing-theme-json-in-wordpress-5-8/"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 a new mechanism}} to configure the editor that enables a finer-grained control and introduces the first step in managing styles for future WordPress releases: the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  file.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Rationale
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The Block Editor API has evolved at different velocities and there are some growing pains, specially in areas that affect themes. Examples of this are: the ability to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://make.wordpress.org/core/2020/01/23/controlling-the-block-editor/"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 control the editor programmatically}}, or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/WordPress/gutenberg/issues/9534"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 a block style system}} that facilitates user, theme, and core style preferences.\
This describes the current efforts to consolidate the various APIs related to styles into a single point \'96 a 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  file that should be located inside the root of the theme directory.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Settings for the block editor
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Instead of the proliferation of theme support flags or alternative methods, the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  files provides a canonical way to define the settings of the block editor. These settings includes things like:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Settings can be controlled per block
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 For more granularity, these settings also work at the block level in 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 .\
Examples of what can be achieved are:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Styles are managed
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 By using the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  file to set style properties in a structured way, the Block Editor can \'93manage\'94 the CSS that comes from different origins (user, theme, and core CSS). For example, if a theme and a user set the font size for paragraphs, we only enqueue the style coming from the user and not the theme\'92s.\
Some of the advantages are:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 CSS Custom Properties: presets & custom
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 There are some areas of styling that would benefit from having shared values that can change across a site.\
To address this need, we\'92ve started to experiment with CSS Custom Properties, aka CSS Variables, in some places:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Specification
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 This specification is the same for the three different origins that use this format: core, themes, and users. Themes can override core\'92s defaults by creating a file called 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 . Users, via the site editor, will also be able to override theme\'92s or core\'92s preferences via a user interface that is being worked on.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "version": 3,\
    "settings": \{\},\
    "styles": \{\},\
    "customTemplates": \{\},\
    "templateParts": \{\}\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Version
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 This field describes the format of the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  file. The latest version is {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.wordpress.org/block-editor/reference-guides/theme-json-reference/theme-json-living/"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 version 3}} introduced in WordPress 6.6.\
New versions are introduced when a breaking change needs to be made. This allows theme authors to choose when to opt-in to the breaking changes and migrate their theme.json files to the new format.\
Older versions of 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  are backwards-compatible and will continue to work with newer versions of WordPress and the Gutenberg plugin. However new features will be developed on the latest version.\
Follow the instructions in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.wordpress.org/block-editor/reference-guides/theme-json-reference/theme-json-migrations/"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 migrating to newer versions}} for details on updating to the latest version.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Settings
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The settings section has the following structure:\
