\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 To maintain backward compatibility, the presets declared via 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 add_theme_support
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  will also generate the CSS Custom Properties. If the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  contains any presets, these will take precedence over the ones declared via 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 add_theme_support
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 .\
Preset classes are attached to the content of a post by some user action. That\'92s why the engine will add 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 !important
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  to these, because user styles should take precedence over theme styles.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa425\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Custom
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3 In addition to create CSS Custom Properties for the presets, the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  also allows for themes to create their own, so they don\'92t have to be enqueued separately. Any values declared within the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 custom
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  field will be transformed to CSS Custom Properties following this naming schema: 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --wp--custom--<variable-name>
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 .\
For example:\
Note that the name of the variable is created by adding 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  in between each nesting level and 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 camelCase
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  fields are transformed to 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 kebab-case
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa425\partightenfactor0
