\f1\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Top-level styles
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Styles found at the top-level will be enqueued using the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 body
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  selector.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Block styles
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Styles found within a block will be enqueued using the block selector.\
By default, the block selector is generated based on its name such as 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 .wp-block-<blockname-without-namespace>
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 . For example, 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 .wp-block-group
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  for the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 core/group
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  block. There are some blocks that want to opt-out from this default behavior. They can do so by explicitly telling the system which selector to use for them via the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 __experimentalSelector
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  key within the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 supports
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  section of its 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 block.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  file. Note that the block needs to be registered server-side for the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 __experimentalSelector
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  field to be available to the style engine.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa425\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Referencing a style
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3 A block can be styled using a reference to a root level style. This feature is supported by Gutenberg.\uc0\u8232 If you register a background color for the root using styles.color.background:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 "styles": \{\
        "color": \{\
            "background": "var(--wp--preset--color--primary)"\
        \}\
    \}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 You can use 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 ref: "styles.color.background"
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  to re-use the style for a block:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "color": \{\
        "text": \{ "ref": "styles.color.background" \}\
    \}\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa425\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Element styles
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3 In addition to top-level and block-level styles, there\'92s the concept of elements that can be used in both places. There\'92s a closed set of them:\
Supported by Gutenberg:\
Supported by WordPress:\
If they\'92re found in the top-level the element selector will be used. If they\'92re found within a block, the selector to be used will be the element\'92s appended to the corresponding block.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa534\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Element pseudo selectors
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3 Pseudo selectors 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 :hover
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 :focus
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 :focus-visible
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 :visited
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 :active
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 :link
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 :any-link
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  are supported by Gutenberg.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 "elements": \{\
        "link": \{\
            "color": \{\
                "text": "green"\
            \},\
            ":hover": \{\
                "color": \{\
                    "text": "hotpink"\
                \}\
            \}\
        \}\
    \}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa425\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Variations
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3 A block can have a \'93style variation,\'94 as defined in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.wordpress.org/block-editor/reference-guides/block-api/block-registration/#styles-optional"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 block.json specification}}. Theme authors can define the style attributes for an existing style variation using the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  file. Styles for unregistered style variations will be ignored.\
Note that variations are a \'93block concept\'94\'97they only exist when bound to blocks. The 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  specification respects this distinction by only allowing 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 variations
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  at the block level, not the top level. It\'92s also worth highlighting that only variations defined in the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 block.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  file of the block or via 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 register_block_style
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  on the server are considered \'93registered\'94 for 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  styling purposes.\
For example, this is how to provide styles for the existing 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 plain
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  variation for the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 core/quote
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  block:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "version": 3,\
    "styles": \{\
        "blocks": \{\
            "core/quote": \{\
                "variations": \{\
                    "plain": \{\
                        "color": \{\
                            "background": "red"\
                        \}\
                    \}\
                \}\
            \}\
        \}\
    \}\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The resulting CSS output is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 .wp-block-quote.is-style-plain \{\
    background-color: red;\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 It is also possible for multiple block types to share the same variation styles. There are two recommended ways to define such shared styles:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  partial files\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
programmatically, using 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 register_block_style
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa534\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Variation Theme.json Partials
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3 Like theme style variation partials, those for block style variations reside within a theme\'92s 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 /styles
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  directory. However, they are differentiated from theme style variations by the introduction of a top-level property called 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 blockTypes
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 . The 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 blockTypes
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  property is an array of block types for which the block style variation has been registered.\
Additionally, a 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 slug
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  property is available to provide consistency between the different sources that may define block style variations and to decouple the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 slug
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  from the translatable 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 title
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  property.\
The following is an example of a 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  partial that defines styles for the \'93Variation A\'94 block style for the Group, Columns, and Media & Text block types:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "$schema": "https://schemas.wp.org/trunk/theme.json",\
    "version": 3,\
    "title": "Variation A",\
    "slug": "variation-a",\
    "blockTypes": [ "core/group", "core/columns", "core/media-text" ],\
    "styles": \{\
        "color": \{\
            "background": "#eed8d3",\
            "text": "#201819"\
        \},\
        "elements": \{\
            "heading": \{\
                "color": \{\
                    "text": "#201819"\
                \}\
            \}\
        \},\
        "blocks": \{\
            "core/group": \{\
                "color": \{\
                    "background": "#825f58",\
                    "text": "#eed8d3"\
                \},\
                "elements": \{\
                    "heading": \{\
                        "color": \{\
                            "text": "#eed8d3"\
                        \}\
                    \}\
                \}\
            \}\
        \}\
    \}\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa534\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Programmatically Registering Variation Styles
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3 As an alternative to 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  partials, you can register variation styles at the same time as registering the variation itself through 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 register_block_style
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 . This is done by registering the block style for an array of block types while also passing a \'93style object\'94 within the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 style_data
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  option.\
The example below registers a \'93Green\'94 variation for the Group and Columns blocks. Note that the style object passed via 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 style_data
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  follows the same shape as the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 styles
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  property of a 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  partial.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 register_block_style(\
    array( 'core/group', 'core/columns' ),\
    array(\
        'name'       => 'green',\
        'label'      => __( 'Green' ),\
        'style_data' => array(\
            'color'    => array(\
                'background' => '#4f6f52',\
                'text'       => '#d2e3c8',\
            ),\
            'blocks'   => array(\
                'core/group' => array(\
                    'color' => array(\
                        'background' => '#739072',\
                        'text'       => '#e3eedd',\
                    ),\
                ),\
            ),\
            'elements' => array(\
                'link'   => array(\
                    'color'  => array(\
                        'text' => '#ead196',\
                    ),\
                    ':hover' => array(\
                        'color' => array(\
                            'text' => '#ebd9b4',\
                        ),\
                    ),\
                ),\
            ),\
        ),\
    )\
);\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 customTemplates
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Supported in WordPress from version 5.9.\
Within this field themes can list the custom templates present in the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 templates
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  folder. For example, for a custom template named 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 my-custom-template.html
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  can declare what post types can use it and what\'92s the title to show the user:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "version": 3,\
    "customTemplates": [\
        \{\
            "name": "my-custom-template",\
            "title": "The template title",\
            "postTypes": [\
                "page",\
                "post",\
                "my-cpt"\
            ]\
        \}\
    ]\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 templateParts
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Supported in WordPress from version 5.9.\
Within this field themes can list the template parts present in the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 parts
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  folder. For example, for a template part named 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 my-template-part.html
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  can declare the area term for the template part entity which is responsible for rendering the corresponding block variation (Header block, Footer block, etc.) in the editor. Defining this area term in the json will allow the setting to persist across all uses of that template part entity, as opposed to a block attribute that would only affect one block. Defining area as a block attribute is not recommended as this is only used \'91behind the scenes\'92 to aid in bridging the gap between placeholder flows and entity creation.\
Currently block variations exist for \'93header\'94 and \'93footer\'94 values of the area term, any other values and template parts not defined in the json will default to the general template part block. Variations will be denoted by specific icons within the editor\'92s interface, will default to the corresponding semantic HTML element for the wrapper (this can also be overridden by the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 tagName
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  attribute set on the template part block), and will contextualize the template part allowing more custom flows in future editor improvements.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "version": 3,\
    "templateParts": [\
        \{\
            "name": "my-template-part",\
            "title": "Header",\
            "area": "header"\
        \}\
    ]\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 patterns
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Supported in WordPress from version 6.0.\
Within this field themes can list patterns to register from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wordpress.org/patterns/"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Pattern Directory}}. The 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 patterns
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  field is an array of pattern 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 slugs
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  from the Pattern Directory. Pattern slugs can be extracted by the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 url
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  in single pattern view at the Pattern Directory. For example in this url 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 https://wordpress.org/patterns/pattern/partner-logos` the slug is
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 partner-logos`.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "version": 3,\
    "patterns": [ "short-text-surrounded-by-round-images", "partner-logos" ]\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Developing with theme.json
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 It can be difficult to remember the theme.json settings and properties and which versions of WordPress support which settings while you develop, so it can be helpful to use the provided JSON schema for theme.json.\
Many code editors support JSON schema and can provide help like tooltips, autocomplete, or schema validation right in your editor.\
Theme.json schemas for each WordPress version are available at 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 https://schemas.wp.org/wp/\{\{version\}\}/theme.json`. For example a schema for WordPress 5.8 is available at
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 https://schemas.wp.org/wp/5.8/theme.json`. To ensure that you\'92re only using features available to your users, it\'92s best to use the oldest version that your theme supports.\
The latest schema including all the latest changes from the Gutenberg plugin is available at `https://schemas.wp.org/trunk/theme.json`.\
Check your editor\'92s documentation for JSON schema support. In Visual Studio Code, for example, you need to add 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 "$schema": "https://schemas.wp.org/wp/x.x/theme.json"
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  as a top-level property of your theme.json file, but other editors may be configured differently.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
