\f1\b0\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 The naming schema of CSS Custom Properties
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 One thing you may have noticed is the naming schema used for the CSS Custom Properties the system creates, including the use of double hyphen, 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , to separate the different \'93concepts\'94. Take the following examples.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 Presets
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  such as 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --wp--preset--color--black
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  can be divided into the following chunks:\

\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 Custom
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  properties such as 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --wp--custom--line-height--body
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 , which can be divided into the following chunks:\
The 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  as a separator has two functions:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Why using \'97 as a separator?
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 We could have used any other separator, such as a single 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 -
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 .\
However, that\'92d have been problematic, as it\'92d have been impossible to tell how 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --wp-custom-line-height-template-header
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  should be converted back into an object, unless we force theme authors not to use 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 -
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  in their variable names.\
By reserving 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  as a category separator and let theme authors use 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 -
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  for word-boundaries, the naming is clearer: 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --wp--custom--line-height--template-header
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 How settings under \'93custom\'94 create new CSS Custom Properties
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The algorithm to create CSS Variables out of the settings under the \'93custom\'94 key works this way:\
This is for clarity, but also because we want a mechanism to parse back a variable name such 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --wp--custom--line-height--body
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  to its object form in theme.json. We use the same separation for presets.\
For example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "version": 3,\
    "settings": \{\
        "custom": \{\
            "lineHeight": \{\
                "body": 1.7\
            \},\
            "font-primary": "-apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Oxygen-Sans, Ubuntu, Cantarell, 'Helvetica Neue', sans-serif"\
        \}\
    \}\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 A few notes about this process:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "version": 3,\
    "settings": \{\
        "custom": \{\
            "line--height": \{ // DO NOT DO THIS\
                "body": 1.7\
            \}\
        \}\
    \}\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Global Stylesheet
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 In WordPress 5.8, the CSS for some of the presets defined by WordPress (font sizes, colors, and gradients) was loaded twice for most themes: in the block-library stylesheet plus in the global stylesheet. Additionally, there were slight differences in the CSS in both places.\
In WordPress 5.9 release, CSS of presets are consolidated into the global stylesheet, that is now loaded for all themes. Each preset value generates a single CSS Custom Property and a class, as in:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 /* CSS Custom Properties for the preset values */\
body \{\
  --wp--preset--<PRESET_TYPE>--<PRESET_SLUG>: <DEFAULT_VALUE>;\
  --wp--preset--color--pale-pink: #f78da7;\
  --wp--preset--font-size--large: 36px;\
  /* etc. */\
\}\
\
/* CSS classes for the preset values */\
.has-<PRESET_SLUG>-<PRESET_TYPE> \{ ... \}\
.has-pale-pink-color \{ color: var(--wp--preset--color--pale-pink) !important; \}\
.has-large-font-size \{ font-size: var(--wp--preset--font-size--large) !important; \}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 For themes to override the default values they can use the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  and provide the same slug. Themes that do not use a 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  can still override the default values by enqueuing some CSS that sets the corresponding CSS Custom Property.\

\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 Example
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  (sets a new value for the default large font size):\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 body \{\
 --wp--preset--font-size--large: <NEW_VALUE>;\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Specificity for link colors provided by the user
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 In WordPress 5.8, when a user selected a link color for a specific block we attached a class to that block in the form of 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 .wp-element-<ID>
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  and then enqueued the following style:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 .wp-element-<ID> a \{ color: <USER_COLOR_VALUE> !important; \}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 While this preserved user preferences at all times, the specificity was too strong and conflicted with some blocks with legit uses of an HTML element that shouldn\'92t be considered links. To {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/WordPress/gutenberg/pull/34689"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 address this issue}}, in WordPress 5.9 release, the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 !important
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  was removed and updated the corresponding blocks to style the a elements with a specificity higher than the user link color, which now is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 .wp-element-<ID> a \{ color: <USER_COLOR_VALUE>; \}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 As a result of this change, it\'92s now the block author and theme author\'92s responsibility to make sure the user choices are respected at all times and that the link color provided by the user (specificity 011) is not overridden.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 What is blockGap and how can I use it?
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 For blocks that contain inner blocks, such as Group, Columns, Buttons, and Social Icons, 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 blockGap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  controls the spacing between inner blocks. For 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 blockGap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  to work, the block must also opt in to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.wordpress.org/block-editor/reference-guides/block-api/block-supports/#layout"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 layout
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \ulc2  block support}}, which provides layout styles that can be adjusted via the block spacing controls. Depending on the layout of the block, the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 blockGap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  value will be output as either a vertical margin or a 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 gap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  value. In the editor, the control for the 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 blockGap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  value is called 
\f4\i \cf2 \cb3 Block spacing
\f1\i0 \cf2 \cb3 , located in the Dimensions panel.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf5 \cb3 \{\
    "version": 3,\
    "settings": \{\
        "spacing": \{\
            "blockGap": true,\
        \}\
    \},\
    "styles": \{\
        "spacing": \{\
            "blockGap": "1.5rem"\
        \}\
    \}\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The setting for 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 blockGap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  is either a boolean or 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 null
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  value and is 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 null
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  by default. This allows an extra level of control over style output. The 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 settings.spacing.blockGap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  setting in a 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  file accepts the following values:\
The value defined for the root 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 styles.spacing.blockGap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  style is also output as a CSS property, named 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 --wp--style--block-gap
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 Why does it take so long to update the styles in the browser?
\f3\b \cf2 \cb3 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 When you are actively developing with theme.json you may notice it takes 30+ seconds for your changes to show up in the browser, this is because 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 theme.json
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3  is cached. To remove this caching issue, set either {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.wordpress.org/advanced-administration/debug/debug-wordpress/#wp_debug"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 WP_DEBUG}} or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.wordpress.org/advanced-administration/debug/debug-wordpress/#script_debug"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 SCRIPT_DEBUG}} to \'91true\'92 in your {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.wordpress.org/advanced-administration/wordpress/wp-config/"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 wp-config.php}}. This tells WordPress to skip the cache and always use fresh data.}